	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">11 July 2012 16:42</span>

	                    Letter from DCC Steve Allen


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p class="MsoNormal">This letter was sent by Deputy Chief Constable
Steve Allen to the Editor of the Scottish Daily Mail to provide
clarification on a recent article carried in the newspaper.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p>DAILY MAIL ARTICLE &ndash; 4 JULY 2012</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Dear Sir</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">My purpose in writing is to give some context
and explanation to information that has been provided to you and
which, on reflection, has allowed too much scope for
misinterpretation by you in a way that acts against the public
interest.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">I refer to your article of 4 July 2012
entitled &lsquo;<em>The guilty officers who are allowed to stay in the
police&rsquo;</em>.&nbsp; The information outlined within the article is
based on a series of freedom of information requests linked to
officers with convictions.&nbsp; I note from a Lothian &amp;
Borders perspective that a return of 111 was provided to you and
has subsequently been used within the article.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The question you posed to Lothian &amp;
Borders Police was&nbsp; &lsquo;<em>How many officers and PCSOs that
currently work for the service have criminal
convictions</em>&rsquo;.&nbsp; It is noted that the term criminal
conviction is not defined within your correspondence.&nbsp; I
understand that the Force Information Unit extended the response to
include recordable offences. This goes beyond the traditional
definition of a criminal conviction linked to the outcome of a
criminal prosecution concluding in a judgement of guilt.&nbsp; The
figures provided to you by the Force Information Unit encompassed
all recordable offences.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">This approach does not appear to have been
consistent across Scotland and has led to a misleading comparison
being made.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The information you were provided included
road traffic offences linked to legislation such as the Road
Traffic Regulation Act 1984 and the Motorway (Traffic) Speed Limit
Regulations 1974.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">These offences are commonly referred to as
&lsquo;speeding&rsquo;.&nbsp; Approx 85% of the figure provided to you relate
to such offences and are commonly dealt with by means of a Fixed
Penalty Notice.&nbsp; I do not condone the actions of persons
breaching the above statutory provisions, however, they are not
generally considered to cast doubt on an individual&rsquo;s suitability
to serve as a police officer.&nbsp; That being said, any officer
who receives a Fixed Penalty Notice is required to report it to the
Deputy Chief Constable and the particular circumstances
reviewed.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">I also note you report that a Chief Inspector
is still employed within Lothian &amp; Borders Police after being
found guilty of drug offences. I can categorically state that the
information you have published is incorrect.&nbsp; I have looked at
the information we have provided and can understand how you have
reached this conclusion.&nbsp; However, the correct interpretation
is that the case of the Chief Inspector (which was widely reported)
relates to Data Protection Act offences.&nbsp; The officer was
suspended prior to conviction and never returned to duty.&nbsp; The
officer is no longer a member of Lothian and Borders Police.&nbsp;
A Constable was convicted of drug offences (again a widely reported
case) and that officer too was suspended long before conviction and
likewise never returned to duty prior to leaving the
organisation.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">I hope you can understand how the reported
facts differ in such a substantial way from the reality that I
would be concerned about the unnecessary damage caused to public
confidence.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoBodyText2">I am not complaining about your article but
imagine that you are likely to make future use of some of the
information upon which you base it.&nbsp; My staff and I would be
very happy to assist you in understanding the context around such
information should such an opportunity be afforded us in order to
ensure that such a misleading interpretation is not repeated.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Yours sincerely</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Steve Allen</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Deputy Chief Constable</p>
